                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d183">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">651.116 Nitrate/73: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-11-23T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 23, 1934—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received November 23—10:25
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>869. Reference my No. 862 of November 20, 7 p.m. In order that in approaching
                    Foreign Office in sense of Department’s telegram No. 469 of November 21, 6 p.m.,
                    certain points raised in Foreign Office note may simultaneously be refuted it
                    would be appreciated if Department would telegraph whether as alleged American
                    producers were parties to nitrates cartel instituted in June and July at Basel
                    and London. Aikman<note n="79" xml:id="d183fn79">T. T. Aikman, European
                        representative of the Barrett Company.</note> states that the Barrett
                    Company was not a party and that so far as he is aware neither were other
                    American producers.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Straus</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
